        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>450 W. Randolph St.<lb/>
                Chicago&#44; July 11. 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/>
                Dear friend and colleague&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Accept hearty thanks for your kind note&#33;  I am<lb/> always <hi rend="underline">so</hi> glad to see your dear handwriting.  Retired<lb/> as I live and having very slight intercourse with any<lb/> of my colleagues&#44; either here or elsewhere&#45;&#45;the sole one<lb/> whom I meet oftener is old&#44; dear <sic>liebmann</sic> Adler&#44; in<lb/> this city&#45;&#45;you can imagine that your words are welcome<lb/> and refreshing to me.<lb/></p>
            <p>And here permit me to say that I should be grateful<lb/> for any criticism you would make on anything I publicly<lb/> say or write.  So&#44; as to my &#91;Hebrew&#93; article&#44; I am well<lb/> aware that it might be complemented by drawing from and<lb/> referring to sources to which I have no access.  I should<lb/> not wonder&#44; f. i.&#44; that by many of the Jewish Italian<lb/> authors of the 17. century the &#91;Hebrew&#93; and its introduction in the Synag.<lb/> should have been mentioned or discussed.  But can I know<lb/> this&#63;  My library is a very small one and I have no other<lb/> one in this city which I could make use of.<lb/></p>
            <p>Permit me a question.  I know that &#91;Hebrew&#93; is a<lb/> part of the Sephardic ritual.  But how is it with the<lb/> psalms &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;  Are in the &#34;Portuguese&#34; Synagogues the six<lb/> psalms 95 to 99 and 29 chanted before &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and the ps. 92 x 93<lb/></p>
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>after &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; as it is done according to &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;  I have<lb/> not a Sephardic Siddur in my possession&#44; so that I could<lb/> know this.  Further&#58; Is in the Portuguese congregations<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; recited before or after &#91;Hebrew&#93; on Friday evenings&#63;<lb/>  The sources at my command are self contradicting on this<lb/> point.<lb/></p>
            <p>I should think&#44; my dear Mr. Morais&#44; that you too might<lb/> feel it sometimes keenly and painfully that you have no<lb/> access to a large and comprehensive Hebrew library.  But<lb/> there is a fine nucleus of one in your city&#44;&#45;&#45;the Leeser<lb/> library.  You ought to take steps that this library be&#45;<lb/>comes systematically enlarged and that additional books<lb/> are bought for it regularly every year.  Is it not possible<lb/> in Philad<hi rend="sup">a</hi> to interest a number of Jewish men in such<lb/> an endeavor&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Now I must bring my <hi rend="underline">causerie</hi> to an end.  It<lb/> would be wrong to tire you <hi rend="underline">too</hi> much with my aim&#45;<lb/>less writings.<lb/></p>
            <p>With best regards&#44; as ever&#44;<lb/>
                yours sincerely<lb/>
                B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
            </body>
